deck_excerpt: Just a random idea, that probably won't work.
deck_description:
This is just a weird idea I had. The idea is to mill your edge imp and fluffal monsters using tearlaments, then you use frightfur fusion to fusion summon using those fluffals and edge imps.

First of all, this probably isn't great synergy. After all, there's the risk that I lose all of my frightfur fusions to those mill effects. On the bright side, I can use fluffal bear, fluffal dolphin, fluffal wings and toy vendor as a sort of draw/discard engine. Unfortunately, since this is kind of on a budget, I'm only using one copy of tearlaments reinoheart and no field spells (I know, the idea of "budget tearlaments" is wishful thinking. Playing them the way they're played in tournaments is a little out of reach though).

Overall, I feel like this would be fun to play, but it certainly wouldn't win any tournaments. I know there's not really a lot to improve this deck, but if you have any feedback, that is welcome.

deck_excerpt: Draw 4, banish your opponent's deck, and win in a grindgame vs. meta with Naturia Runick!
deck_description:
In a Round 4 feature match in YCS Dortmund, Naturia Runick solidly beat Branded Tearlament! It was absolutely facinating to watch Dinh-kha Bui methodically pick apart and control a hyper aggressive deck and out resource it in a grindgame. Watching that series as an avid Naturia player encouraged me to adopt the strategy and make a guide for it, so here it is, a Beginner's Guide to Naturia Runick!

Shoutout to Dinh-kha Bui for first popularizing this strategy with his top 64 YCS Dortmund run - only losing once in the swiss rounds!

This deck is a variant of my earlier deck guide, Naturia Ishizu, feel free to check it out as well. :)

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

  • Forming the bulk of the deck and it's core strategy, Runick cards consist of 20 cards.

3 Tip, 3 Flashing Fire, 3 Freezing Curses, 3 Destruction, 3 Slumber, 2 Smiting Storm, 1 Dispelling, and 2 Fountain. In the Extra Deck there are 2 Hugin, and 1 Geri.

  • Forming the deck’s core strategy, the Naturia cards in the Main Deck consist of 12 cards:

3 Camellia, 3 Molcricket, 1 Sunflower, 2 Blessing and 3 Sacred Tree. In the Extra Deck there are 1 Beast, and 1 Barkion.

  • The milling and GY manipulation powerhouses of this deck, the Ishizu cards in the maindeck consists of 9 cards:

3 Keldo, 3 Mudora and 3 Kelbek. Keldo and Mudora shuffle GY cards, and Kelbek is a handtrap/mill enabler.

  • The anti-GY Bystial package consist of 4 cards:

3 Bystial Magnamhut and 1 Druiswyrm.

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

With Runick's draw 3/deck banishing coupled with Naturia's control/resource generation, you should be able to out-resource your opponent in a grind game. Grind games are forced out as you banish your opponent's key cards from deck, control the board/GY, and negate everything with Naturia Sunflower/Beast and Runick spells.

Going first, the gameplan is to set up Runick Fountain, draw 1-4 cards and a level 10 Synchro of choice. A hand that has access to Naturia Molcricket/Camellia + Runick Fountain can accomplish this.

Here is the deck's signature combo, courtesy of Dinh-kha Bui (Top 64 YCS Dortmund) for inventing this combo!
  1. Special summon Hugin from RD with any Runick card.
  2. Discard any card with Hugin's effect to search for Runick Fountain. (This is best done in draw/standby phase so your opponent cannot Droll you)
  3. Tribute Molcricket for Camellia. Or if you have Camellia already in hand, normal summon it.
  4. Activate Camillia's on-summon effect to mill Sacred Tree from deck to grave. 
  5. Sacred Tree searches Blessing. 
  6. Synchro Camellia + Hugin for Stardust Charge Warrior to draw 1 card.
  7. Activate Naturia Blessing to summon Camellia from GY.
  8. Synchro Camellia + Stardust Charge Warrior for your level 10 Synchro of choice. I personally go for Chengying, since his synergy with Runick is incredible, he's hard to remove, and he protects your lifepoints and low attack monsters.
  9. If you have Runick Tip/Slumber, you can activate them turn 1 to trigger Runick Fountain's effect to shuffle back Runick cards in the GY to draw 1-3 cards. If you have extra level 4s, you can make Abyss Dweller or any other rank 4 of choice to further lock down your opponent.
  10. During your opponent's turn, you can summon Molcricket from your GY when you opponent summons from the extra deck. Molcricket can tribute itself to tag out into Camellia/Sunflower for monster negates, mills, and resource generation.
With this combo, you drew 1-4 cards, a strong defensive monster that can banish field/GY cards, follow-up for next turn, GY-setup for both Naturia and Runick and multiple in-hand interruptions (Bystial, Kelbek, Runick spells).

When discarding cards with Hugin's effect to search Runick Fountain, its ideal to discard Naturia Sacred Tree (Naturia search) and Ishizu cards (Interruption/mills)!
 
When milling with Camellia, always send Sacred Tree so it can search Naturia Blessing. Naturia Blessing is a monster reborn that is not once per turn!

Going second, opponent's boards are broken by interrupting your opponent at key moments with handtraps like the Bystial cards, Ishizu cards and Naturia cards.

Remember, Naturia Molcricket can summon itself from the GY if your opponent summons from the Extra Deck, so you can potentially play turn 1! If you somehow summon Molcricket in this turn 1 situation, tribute Molcricket to summon Camellia + Sunflower, which represents 2 monster negates + 1 search!

If your deck was milled by your opponent, it will help you out on the crack-back during your turn, since a decent GY set-up enables more plays, resources and interruptions for the Naturia player.

When your opponent's turn 1 is complete, you can methodically pick apart your opponent's board depending on which Runick spells you have in your hand. If you can't fully break your opponent's board, you can always summon level 4 Geri, The Runick Fangs, and XYZ summon with another level 4 to stall for time/resources with Bagooska.

When you finally break your opponent's board, you can go for the ideal turn 1 set-up to force a grindgame where you out-resource your opponent with a combination of Runick + Naturia cards.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • Before milling with Kelbek, try to make and activate Abyss Dweller first so that your opponent doesn't plus with your mills.
  • Remember that Runick Fountain can draw cards during your turn AND your opponent's turn! You can theoretically draw 6 cards before it's your turn again (given you have proper GY and hand set-up)! Remember to keep the GY and hand in mind when you use Runick spells.
  • Ishizu shufflers effectively shut down Runick Fountain's draw effect since it targets Runick spells in GY to shuffle back into your deck. Try to clear your opponent's GY shufflers before attempting to activate Fountain's draw effect!
  • Runick spells skip only 1 battle phase - battle phase is still an option for finishing off your opponent's life points. If your opponent has no more resources and you can attack for game, you can still enter the battle phase after you've skipped one earlier to finish off your opponent!
  • Two level 6s -> Beatrice can mill any card from deck. Ideally, Beatrice is used to mill Naturia Sacred Tree for a search. Two level 6 monsters can be summoned with the Bystial cards, or a level 6 synchro summon.
  • If you make Chengying, its effect to banish your opponent's card in their field and GY can be triggered as a quick effect by the Ishizu cards, Runick spells and Bystial monsters. 
  • If you get interrupted too much and you're in a bad position, make Bagooska to stall for resources. 
  • Decks that counter Tearlaments are usually also bad match-ups for this deck - like Floowandereeze and Dracoslayers (the variant that turbos out Necrovalley). Be sure to side appropriately for those match-ups. Luckily, this deck naturally outs anti-GY floodgates like Macro Cosmos, Necrovalley and Dimension Fissure with Runick spells.

 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

Once again, shoutout to Dinh-kha Bui for inventing Naturia Runick. It's such a fun and cool strategy!

I found this deck personally hard to pilot, since you have to keep track of soooo many things like your GY, your opponent's GY, the amount of resources in hand, whether you can break your opponent's board, what possible combo lines you can do, how much cards you draw, etc. But man, is it fun to play!

Alternative win conditions like controlling and milling your opponent into submission always had a special place in my heart, and Runick cards just made this playstyle competitive!

It's also very cool that Runick cards are from first person perspective - it's like you're DOOMGUY blasting away your enemies, or your Skyrim hero fighting monsters in a fantasy world! Now we can live out our video game imagination in Yugioh!

The play style also kind of reminds me of Sky Striker (rest in pieces Raye T__T), and Runick is the closest I'm going to get to playing that fan-favourite deck this format, since my favourite mecha pilot isn't viable in the meta anymore.

Anyways, Runick Naturia is a viable contender that can comfortably face Tearlaments this meta, and I'm definitely trying this out in Locals and online duels!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: For when Tributing just ain't cutting it.
deck_description:
Really the only Deck I use on Master Duel. Basic plan is to get Geartown on field and break it, either with Ancient Gear Balista or Ancient Gear Catapult. Summon Wyvern into Frame, draw Box with Wyvern, draw any 500 defense card you may need or just need to mill, use Frame's effect on field to discard said card or other brick, grab Ancient Gear Fusion, play Ancient Gear Fusion, make sure you have atleast one other Ancient Gear monster in hand, Fusion summon Megaton or Giant if possible, run over your opponent. If your opponent pops Megaton, you got Ultimate golem as backup into normal Golem if it all goes from bad to worse. You'll be searching for a way to get Chaos Giant on the field.
If you need something on the field but dont want to waste Megaton or Giant, Howitzer is a 1k burn immune to card effects; can waste a card effect if opponent isn't paying attention and forces a battle for a Ancient Gear search. Alternatively instead of Howitzer, if you have Geartown and/or Infinitrack Anchor Drill in hand, play Geartown, play Infinitrack to bring two monsters on field, Link-off into Ancient Gear Balista, either add Box or another Ancient Gear monster with Ancient Gear Balista's effect, use Balista's second effect to pop Geatown, use Geartown GY effect to special summon Wyvern, draw box(or another Ancient Gear monster if you already have.) with Wyvern effect, activate Box in hand, draw desired card like Frame or another Infinitrack if your hand is populated.

I recently added Harbinger and Called by because of the Ash Blossom & DBE Spam thanks to Verte being unbanned over here on Master Duel. This might not be a great deck, but it's a good one for what it is at least. Ra is here incase you need more monster removal.

deck_excerpt: Buster blader, Branded fusion, Slifer the sky dragon, Dogmatika
deck_description:
This is the best version of a buster blader deck i could come up with. It has a lot of spicy cards like Slifer the sky dragon, and many different 1 card combo's. You can go a lot of different directions. End on a winda lock, buster blader lock, Slifer floodgate (or even a ra's diciple lock), the branded fusions or a combination of those.

some nice combo's below:

Combo 1: Activate nadir & search maximus. Send apkalone to grave. Add schism & discard it. Now summon maximus and activate to dump construct & titaniclad. Construct activates and returns schim from the grave to the hand. Set schism. End phase: titaniclad adds fleur to the hand. With this combo you can lock your opponent into the winda-lock, and you also have a dragon in the grave to make prologue live. 

Combo 2: activate branded fusion and summon lubellion by sending albaz and buster dragon to the grave. Next turn, activate prologue and summon buster dragon + buster blader. Equip buster dragon to buster blader. Now you have the full buster lock. 

Combo 3: Activate branded fusion and make brigrand by sending albaz and slifer to the grave. next turn, activate sky god revived and summon slifer on the field while drawing 6 cards. This combo is busted if you can pull it off. 

Combo 4: activate branded fusion and make titaniclad by sending albaz and eldlich to the grave. Because Eldlich is lvl 10, titaniclad will be 3900atk permanently. Now you can also summon eldlich by destroying a spell/trap (preferably branded opening) to have a 3900atk monster and 3500atk monster on the field. It's very handy to otk your opponent unexpectedly. 

Combo 5: add ra's deciple and branded expulsion to the deck. Activate branded fusion, summon albion by sending albaz and ra's diciple to the grave. Now search/set expuslion. Next turn: activate expulsion, tribute the albion and summon ra's diciple to the opponents field. The opponent is now locked to normal summons only, and diciple is really hard to get rid of giving you time to collect all cards you need to go for game. 

Combo 6: activate branded fusion and make lubbellion by sending albaz and dark magician to the grave. Activate lubbelion and summon dragoon with the dark magician. Now dragoon also has the effect to pop 1 monster and do burn damage equal to it's attack. Dragoon also offers much needed protection against backrow. 

There are some other combo's but these are the ones i use most often. The deck is insane and should not be underestimated!

deck_excerpt: Have a bunch of rocks in your hand? Well, I have a solution.
deck_description:
When the Vernusylphs were first announced, I had some twinkles appear when I began to think about how this would impact the largely EARTH-based Adamancipator+Rock deck. It's one of my absolute favorite decks, but has suffered pretty extensively as Konami cleaned up many of their broken link monsters over the last few banlists.

The difficulty is that the Vernusylphs lock you into EARTH monster effects. You can summon any attribute, but, if you want to use those monsters on the same turn, they have to be EARTH. This means that common Adamancipator extenders like Raptite are out. In addition, common Nibiru preventers like Borreload Savage and Crystal Wing Dragon are not useful in the role.

However, what the Vernusylphs offer is immense: the ability to summon all the bricky rock monsters in your hand. Add a Koa'ki Meiru off a Supplier? Summon it. Have a Doki Doki or Analyzer, summon them. This completely removes one of Adamancipator's biggest weaknesses in being normal summon reliant. It also allows you to utilize the once heavily used Gogogo monsters to their maximum potential by sending them to the graveyard and then immediately special summoning one of them back to the field. And there are enough decent EARTH rank-4s to keep your engine going and recur some resources that you shouldn't have trouble setting up a nuisance of a board.

Your first turn is often spent setting up a basic board. The Vernusylphs are great, but you are looking for pluses. The three tuners, supplier, and the gogogos will net these for you. Remember to recur an Analyzer using Number 55 (who can also trigger your gogogos in grave). If you are running short on room, make I:P, and then Elf (who can eventually resurrect the I:P). In addition, while Guardian's are easy to summon, Traptrix Rafflesia can serve as a prevention tool against the big rock also.

Game 2, you are probably going to focus on your silver bullets: the naturia synchros, dweller, bagooska. And, going for game, you can always just play regular Adamancipatorfor Dragite access.

Note: The Fenrir's are good, but are not neccesary for a more budget build. You can always play Nibiru, or even more Tackle Crusaders (turns every Vernusylph into Book of Moon or a floodgate bounce).

Cards needed in hand for FTK: ("Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio"/ "Lonefire Blossom"/ "Small World" + Any other monster exept "Elemental HERO Electrum" Matierials) + Any monster (exept "Box of Friends" if "Chain Material" is not in hand)

Cards needed in deck for FTK: "Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra", "Cir, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss", "Graph, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss", "Makyura the Destructor" or "Elemental HERO Shadow Mist", (if "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" is not in hand): "The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak" + "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigadine", 4 Equip Spells("Sword of Deep-Seated" and "Moon Mirror Shield" can be sent to the deck if equiped to a monster that is linked off), (if "Chain Material" is not in hand): 2 Lvl 4 monsters with 0 Def

 

To start of the combo you need to summon "Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio" with one monster in hand to activate his effect.

If you have 2 "Makyura the Destructor" in hand you need to discard one of them here.

Summon "Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra" and add "Fusion Gate" to your hand. Link them off for "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss" and activate its effect to send "Graph, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" to the GY.

Activate "Graph, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" to summon "Cir, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" and link summon "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche".

Activate the effect of "Cir, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss" and summon "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss" from your GY.

Use the effect of "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche" to set "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigadine" to your side of the field by sending "The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak" to the GY.

If you don't have "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" in your hand search it by using "The Phantom Knights of Ancient Cloak" in your GY.

Special summon "The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots" from your hand and activate "The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigadine" to link them off for "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights".

Add "Elemental HERO Sparkman" to your hand.

If your opening hand didn't include 2 "Makyura the Destructor":

  • Use the effect of "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" to special summon "Makyura the Destructor"
  • Link "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" and "Makyura the Destructor" off for "Union Carrier" and activate "Makyura the Destructor"
  • Equip "Box of Friends" to "Union Carrier" by the effect "Union Carrier"
  • Activate "Fusion Gate" and summon 2 "Mudragon of the Swamp" using the monsters on the field and the monster added to your hand by "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights"

If your opening hand did include 2 "Makyura the Destructor":

  • Use the effect of "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" to special summon "Elemental HERO Shadow Mist"
  • Activate Fusion Gate and summon a "Mudragon of the Swamp" using "Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss" and "The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche" as material
  • Link off "Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights" and "Elemental HERO Shadow Mist" for "Cross-Sheep" adding "Elemental HERO Sparkman" to your hand
  • Fusion summon "Elemental HERO Escuridao" using "Elemental HERO Sparkman" and "Makyura the Destructor" from your hand to a zone "Cross-Sheep" points to and summon "Makyura the Destructor" from your GY
  • Link off "Makyura the Destructor" and "Elemental HERO Escuridao" for "Union Carrier" and activate "Makyura the Destructor"
  • Equip "Box of Friends" to "Union Carrier" by the effect "Union Carrier"
  • Fusion summon "Mudragon of the Swamp" using "Union Carrier" and "Elemental HERO Sparkman"

Special summon 2 lvl 4 normal monsters with the effect of "Box of Friends" and overlay them with the 2 "Mudragon of the Swamp" to summon a 4 material "Primathmech Alembertian".

Detatch 4 materials from "Primathmech Alembertian" to search "Chain Material" and activate it.

Fusion summon "Elemental HERO Electrum" and after that "Elemental HERO Gaia" using "Primathmech Alembertian" and "Elemental HERO Sparkman" from deck as material.

Fusion Summon "Idaten the Conqueror Star" using "Elemental HERO Electrum" and "Elemental HERO Gaia" as material

Now begins the loop:

  1. Fusion Summon "Elemental HERO Electrum"
  2. Overlay "Elemental HERO Electrum" and "Idaten the Conqueror Star" for "Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max"
  3. Use the effect of "Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max" detatching "Elemental HERO Electrum" to burn for 2000
  4. Summon "Elemental HERO Gaia" using "Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max" and "Elemental HERO Electrum" as material
  5. Summon "Idaten the Conqueror Star" using "Elemental HERO Gaia" and "Idaten the Conqueror Star" as material

deck_excerpt: crystal, crystal beast, conclave, midrange, control
deck_description:
Hi everybody

After the annoncement of the December 2022 banlist, I decided to update my Crystal Beast Conclave decklist, to fit with the new card restriction (Bye Bye Mystic Mine !). Despite the banlist, I personally think this deck stays a viable choice as a good Anti Meta alternative, with pretty decent match ups overall.

Deck Goal

The main goal of the list is to deplete your opponent's ressources. The deck has the advantage of being composed of multiple tools to adapt your gameplay against specific gameplans (thanks to Field Spells, to the Extra Deck).

Neshy (a youtuber specialized in Crystal Beast content, who has topped recently with a Conclave list) did a really good video, that explain the way to play Crystal Conclave Deck. The video was posted few weeks before the banlist but the explanations of the Conclave list are really clear and good.
Video Link : https://youtu.be/91-OiiG-eS4 

Impact of the Mystic Mine ban

I tested this list in my local to see how the ban impacts the deck performance. IMO, the banlist does not impact so much the deck, as Necrovalley  stays a better field spell to play in the current metagame. Furthermore, in the same idea to counter the main meta decks, Zombie World is another great tool to have in the deck (Good against Floowandereeze, decent against Tear). Then, I decided to replace Mine by Zombie World.

Some Improvements

I see some better improvement in this list, if you have the cards/the money to spend in :

  • Pot of Extravagance => Pot of Prosperity : better to maximize the Extra Deck's use
  • Raigeki => Lightning Storm : more polyvalent, better to manage heavy backrow boards
  • Borrelsword Dragon => Accesscode Talker 

Budget Alternatives

There are some ideas to adapt the deck with budget choices :

  • For the Extra Deck, I highly recommend you to play Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder despite its price. However if you want to replace it or other cards that you deem expensive, you can add an extra copy of Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir and of Abyss Dweller : it will offset the cost of Pot of Extravagance.
  • Raigeki is a good card to play. However, there are budget alternatives of it as Dark Hole or Torrential Tribute.

 

As usual, feel free for you, to give your feedback and ideas in the comment to improve this list :)

Thanks all!

deck_excerpt: Melffy  going to big syncros with a lot of interrupt removal & a tiny tri-brigade engine
deck_description:
Melffy, syncros, & Tri-brigade

Deck is all about getting out strong syncros during your oponents turn through Melffy Pinny and Hop Ear, both easily accessable through Melffy Catty, and setting up lots of interruption and negates during your turn.

Openers are Obedience schooled & Rescue Cat.

- From Obedience schooled you'll go into Naturia beast via Otoshidamashi, Melffy syncros & the tinny tribrigade engine to extend, you should end on Naturia Beast, Tribrigade Ferrijit, Melffys of the forrest, either Melffy Doggy or Wally, Melffy hide and seek, and if you drew a rescue cat Joyous Melffys too.

- From Rescue Cat you'll end on either Shuriag or Utopic Draco Future plus atleast one melffy & Hide and seek, depending on whether banuish their monster a chain after summon (shuriag plus doggy or wally) or a monster negate will be more useful in the matchup.

Generally you game play will be running you oponent out of resources while you generate advantage off thier summons.

The deck faulters against a very early dark ruler no more, but can recover if you've already generatred enough advantage and plays very poorly throguh many flood gates (especially skill drain and barrier stature of the stormwinds).

Lightning storm isn't in the side board becaure I find you'll too often have cards in play to make use of it and you'll generally just be gambling on having it in your opening hand, hance raigeki & feather duster.

If you're siding out I'd usually side out melffys you have 3 of then cut down hopear & rescue cat further down to one of each if needed.

Only played it frequently against Branded-despia, Branded-bystial, Branded-predaplant, Floo, and Swordsoul along with a few very non-meta decks so might need some tweeking if you're up against more meta decks.

Details here a little lacking to aviod showing bottle-knecks, play it a bit and you should be able to work out combo lines and good interrupts relatively easy.

Also Deck was built with the restriction of no cards costing me more than £10 (~$12/€11) so could be improved if you want to make a higher budget version, Baronne de Fleur imediately comes to mind.

deck_excerpt: A new way to run Subterror
deck_description:
This is the deck that I use at locals when I play Subterror.

 

The main stars are obviously Guru and Dragoon.  But the unconventional spice is Shadow-Imprisoning Mirror, Reaper Cherries, and Dimensional Shifter in the main.

 

While Shadow-Imprisoning Mirror turns off Dragoon, you really don't care if you are shutting off an entire deck.  And Dimensional Shifter does hit Fiendess hard.  But if you have that turn skip you don't really care.

 

Cherries hits the Mirrorjade, the Dragoon, Kitkallos, and Spright Elf, some of the BIGGEST problems you would face with the deck.

 

In the extra deck you run the common threats for Cherries.  You also run the Super Polymerization targets.

 

This deck does run Extravagance.  You can run Prosperity.  I opt for Extrav for the simple fact you are running 3 Dragoons and most times you will still always have 1 left after your banish.  And getting the extra card is sometimes nice for Dragoon discards.  Which is what you would use your leftover D. Shifters, Cherries, and Fusions for.  And Prosperity only gets you the 1 for 1.

 

Imperial Iron Wall is in the side for Runick and Floowandereeze (While also have There Can Be Only One in the Main.)  Soul Drain for more Tear hate since we don't use our graves too much.  With Super Polys for the generic fusion targets.

deck_excerpt: Subterror, flood gates, pain and suffering.
deck_description:
Alternate name: Cancer

This is a deck I've been using at locals that is very difficult to deal with due to the amount of floodgates it runs. Its main weakness is target destruction and bad starting hands, which is why all the draw spells and flood gates exist. The deck did run double mystic mine, but with the upcoming banlist that will no longer be an option. 

The extra deck can be whatever you want for the most part, however the predaplant and mudragon are good options to pair with super poly given the current meta. Subterror is also one of the few decks that can properly utilize Dimension Shifter since it only affects Fiendess. However, D-shifter is only good turn 0 or 1, and drawing it afterwards can make it a frustrating card to play since it becomes useless. It also does not stop ash blossom. You can swap out flood gates based on what you think is necessary, however the floodgates I'm currently using do little to nothing to hender Subterror plays.

Lava Golem + Rivalry is a lock you can do to your oppenant if done correctly, and with the field spell you can continously negate the lava golem's attacks. With Tears' ability to flood the board with omni negates among other things, Lava Golem is good for getting rid of such things without them being able to respond.  

With the upcoming banlist, you could potentially swap out D-shifter and put in either 3 Macro Cosmos or Dimensional Barrier. This will however make Fiendess useless and leave you open to spot destruction, which Tears are really good at doing. 

Some people don't like Subtteror Cave Clash, however I like it for recycling the Fiendess's. 

Any advice on making this deck better/more cancerous is welcome. As the deck currently stands, it's a good way to make everyone at your locals hate you and groan whenever they see the deck, which is what I love about it.

is a big brain deck
BRRRR

Vayu Turbo
edison format
by pedro2163

Card choices

I had a really bad time against Royal Decree. So I added one Lyla. Because of this change, I cut completelly the 3rd Dust Tornado too.
Testing Spirit Reaper over Necro Gardna. If milled, Gardna is better but Reaper destroys lots of decks if it's on board.
No Virus because it costs too much ressources and it could fail. I don't want to lose my body just for it.
No Cydra package because we don't have space left ahahha It will be super hard vs Ancient Gear, so wish you luck!
 
Some things to know
 
Vayu synchros survive Royal Oppression, if your opponent doesn't knows you can drain him 800 hp each time, because the banish is not a cost and Vayu is not once per turn.
Royal Oppression's effect cannot be activated during the Damage Step, so it cannot negate Pyramid Turtle/Mystic Tomato/Gorz...
Vayu otk's Dark and Light Dragon, because he needs to negate Vayu in the grave, but because of the same reason as with Royal Oppression, you can recast it again.
If Colossal Fighter dies, he can revive himself.
One fun combo is to equip Armory Arm to Colossal Fighter, its really strong.
Use Dark End to clear Rykos.
You can use your Dust Tornados to pass through Trap Dustshoot.
Tribute Caius banish itself O:), ping 1k for game.
Burial from a diferent dimension destroys Drill Warrior and can fuck up DaD and Krystia.
Book of Moon doesn't kill Spirit Reaper.
Soul Release can help setup your DaD.
If your opponent is not playing any dark type monsters, he will probably side in Consacrated Light. This card is your worst nightmare. You should maybe keep your Lyla, Ryko, Card Trooper and add Rai-Oh to destroy it.

deck_excerpt: Withcrafter , Witches & Dragons , 2022 Witchcrafter , Fun Witchcrafter , Magistus , Magistus Witchcrafter , x-STORMXX-x , Sxx , 2023 Deck
deck_description: Witchcrafter deck aka Witches and Dragons is a fun/casual deck that has been in the making for few months now. It is not perfect and I encourage anyone to play around with the deck as much as you wish. This deck excels at longer games I feel vs its 40 card deck counterparts as it has more then one copy of its main boss monsters to keep you in the game. The deck can be sometimes a bit of a slow start but, after a few rounds it has great potential. The deck can brick but, it often does pretty well in my testing. With its extra deck and so many cards you will find that this deck has options for different end game strategys so the deck does not always feel the same and I think is one of the fun things about this deck. The side deck is really much up for debate and I'm not 100% sold on it but, I think its a ok starting point for some fun plays. I hope you all enjoy this deck. I seen a lot or witchcrafter profiles out there and a lot of them felt the same to me and my main goal was to make a playable witchcrafter deck that had a different spin on it.
This is my first go at making a deck IRL.

Deck info; Deck type: control Dice roll: going FIRST. Pros: - negate opponent cards - bouncing opponent cards. - relatively consistent. - disrupting opponent plays using handtaps\original traps. - removing opponent cards by using powerful effects - the ability to play under your floodgates Cons: this Deck loses to; - starting second. - not opening trap cards. - not opening "altergeist" monsters.

- less advantage if not opening "personal spoofing".

Name:

D.A.G.D.A. (Dual Avatar-Generaider Destroys All)

 

Playstyle:

Mid-range

Control

Beat-down

 

Difficulty:

7/10

 

-High resource management

-Unique play style

-Control oriented gameplan

 

[Deck Breakdown]

 

Generaider Core:

Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms - This card is your big bad boss monster, you almost always want to summon him during your opponent's Draw Phase, His effect consists of a omni-negate and an effect that punishes your opponent for adding a card from their Deck to their Hand, once per turn. 2 copies is more than enough. He is a Garnet and is too valuable to play at only 1 copy, therefore 2 is the perfect number.

Nidhogg, Generaider Boss of Ice - He acts as a walking “Solemn Warning” for Special Summons. He is an additional level 9 monster providing variety in type and attribute. By far one of the weakest boss monsters, but better than nothing.

Utgarda, Generaider Boss of Delusion - All around fantastic monster. For the same cost as Harr’s omni-negate (2 tributes), he targets and banishes any 1 card on the field once per turn. He also provides variety in type and attribute. And has a great defense statistic.

Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light - Fantastic monster. With decent battle statistics, she provides a whole archetype search on Summon. Monster, Spell, Trap, as long as it is a part of the Generaider archetype, she will search it. Perfect for combos.

Vara, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses - The most recent addition to the archetype, she provides a “free” Special Summon, from the Hand or GY, that aids in preventing "Garnets" from ruining your Hands. She also allows you to summon any Generaider monster from either your Hand or GY. All around “House” that perfects the combo potential of the Deck. Most would be confused that I only run 2 but as a similar case with Harr, with 3 copies she just clogs up the Deck.

Loptr, Shadow of the Generaider Bosses - The “Lone Fire” of the Deck, he can tag out himself, or a Generaider token, to Special Summon any Level 9 Generaider monster from the Deck. He acts as a perfect combo starter for the Deck. And if all of that wasn’t good enough, during the opponent's turn he provides a 1000 ATK/DEF stats boost to all Generaider monsters while on the field.

Generaider Boss Stage - By far the most important card in the Deck. The Field Spell. Facilitating the main gameplan of Special Summoning your bosses directly from the Deck, and its second effect provides your field with the remaining tokes to be used as tribute fodder for your bosses effects.

Generaider Boss Quest - A fantastic and fair searcher. At the cost of a “Mulligan” you get to search up to 2 of your Generaider Spells/Traps. Making this card a perfect searcher for Boss Stage. The great thing about it is that the “Cost” to activate the card makes you place a Generaider monster from your Hand on the bottom of your Deck. This is helpful because it allows you to rid of your boss monsters by putting them back in the Deck where they can be summoned by Boss Stage.

Generaider Boss Fight - This card is very interesting. At the cost of giving your opponent a free draw 1 you get to activate Boss Stage directly from your Deck or GY. The cost isn’t particularly bad either because the effect that Boss Stage gives you to Special Summon a monster from your Deck activates in response to your opponent adding a card from their Deck by any means. Meaning that Boss Fight activates Boss Stage and allows its effect to activate. In this case 2 copies is also more than enough.

Generaider Boss Room - This card is an interesting kind of omni-negate. You can only activate it if your opponent activates an effect in response to your Generaider card effect. Starting a chain. But it stops that effect by changing it to a different one that makes both players draw a card. All at the cost of 1 discard. Overall, it is a decent form of protection. Only 1 copy is needed since it's easily searchable.

 

Dual Avatar Engine:

The inclusion of this “engine” so to speak might be confusing to some. However, I hope to justify its inclusion in this Deck with a quick explanation.

The main focus of the engine is the card Dual Avatar Invitation. This card is one of the most "free" cards I have ever seen. At the cost of a single discard you Special Summon as many Dual Avatar Tokens as you can then you get 2 free fusion summons using monsters you control or in your hand. This is quite powerful because 2 of the archetypes' Fusion monsters can be summoned using only the tokens. The catch is that these monsters only gain their good effects if they are summoned using an effect monster. This can be mitigated by using the first Dual Avatar fusion monster you summon as material for the second one. On its own this effect of Dual Avatar Invitation is ok, you get 1 Fusion monster with a decent effect at the cost of a discard, provided you have enough empty monster zones. As far as the Fusion monsters are, the fist Fusion monster, when summoned, grants a free “pop” of any attack position monster your opponent controls, and when summoned with an effect monster as material he grants a small attack and defense boost to all Dual avatar monsters. The feet fusion monster provides a trade off destruction protection, and when summoned using an effect monster she has a once per turn monster negate of a monster special summoned from the Extra Deck. Finally, with the way I have built the package the only “empowered” fusion monster playable is 1 copy of Dual Avatar - Empowered Kon-Gyo whos only significant traits is that he has, once per turn, targeting protection from spells/traps as long as you control at least 2 Fusion monster, and inherently he prevents your opponent from activating any effect at any point when he declares an attack.

Overall, it is clear to see that the strategy is mediocre at best. However when used as a supplementary engine in the Generaider strategy, its potential becomes much better. The package is very consistent, the main Deck monster acts as a 4th copy of the fusion spell, and the Field Spell acts as a 1 card starter that searches the Main Deck monster and provides you with a free tribute for his effect allowing you to summon 2 fusion monsters with all their best effects. At its worst it is a strategy that locks you into Fusion summoning (for the rest of the turn) and provides you with a free "pop" or a situational (Quick Effect) monster negate. Also the cost of 1 discard is mitigated by the fact that many cards in this Deck don’t mind being in the GY and some can activate their effects while in the GY. In the end it might not be the absolute best strategy to run alongside the Generaider core, but there is no doubt that it improves the consistency and ceiling of the Deck, while keeping it fun and unique. Oh and it allows you to play Set Rotation.

 

Level 9 Extenders:

Trias Hierarchia - A fantastic level 9 monster that provides insane advantage. With a strategy that is built around tributing tokens for effects, as it just so happens those tokens are fairies. This monster tributes Fairy monsters to Special Summon itself from your Hand or GY as a Quick Effect. Depending on how many you tribute to Summon it, you gain multiple effects. 1 tribute just summons it. 2 tributes summons it and give you a non-targeting destruction of any 1 card your opponent controls, and if you tribute 3 Fairy monsters you get to summon it, destroy 1 card, and draw 2 cards. Literally Free.

World Legacy Monstrosity - This card is a very powerful Quick Play Spell. It allows you to either special summon a level 9 monster from your hand, or if you already control a level 9 monster, you get to Special Summon up to 2 other level 9 monsters from your Deck as long as they have different types and attributes from the one you control. It is an amazing extender with fantastic combo potential. Perfect for setting up Rank 9 Xyz Summons.

 

Searchers/Draw:

Terraforming - Searches either Field Spell from the Deck for absolutely free.

Set Rotation - Because I play 2 different strategies that use Field Spells, it acts as another copy of Terraforming, but at Quick Play speed.

Kuji-Kiri Curse - At 2 copies this card is yet another card that allows you to get rid of any "Garnets" in your hand by sending them to your GY to draw 2 cards. Overall it adds to the consistency of the Deck and allows you to set up by putting monsters that can activate their effects in the GY, in the GY. Thus giving you even more advantage.

 

“Tech”:

As for the “Tech” cards I play they are more budget friendly, but seeing as the rest of the Deck and Extra Deck are pretty inexpensive you do have the option to play more expensive staples. Effect Veiler could be switched out with Infinite Impermanence and Raigeki could be switched out with Evenly Matched, it is your choice. But as far as what I play with, it gets the job done.

 

Extra Deck:

To keep the rest of this explanation short I won't go over every card in the Extra Deck. For the Dual Avatar package 2 copies of the small Fusion monsters allows for the longevity of the strategy allowing you to use the Fusion spell more than once in a Duel improving the “grind game”. The rest of the Extra Deck consists of a toolbox of Xyz/Link monsters that can be Summoned using your Main Deck boss monsters. They contribute to the strategy providing powerful effects and stats improving the ceiling of the Deck significantly.

deck_description: the 1st place deck for the 8th keep your game on! monthly from the noajenk discord!

Basic ghoti list, can definitely be improved. Deck wants to go first and almost always dies going second. Beautunaful searches leaffish, you may want to cut down on a copy because it can sometimes be bricky. Dragite and crystal wing aren't made often but sometimes come up. If you want some more going second power, cut chengying to add -Abyss Keeper. The deck doesn't play eanoc because he's really bad and most of the traps aren't great. The deck functions well in midrange and can't flood the board until turn 2/3. Use terraforming and depths to bait ash. If you have two tuners and a 6, you can make deep beyond on opp turn. 

 

Combos:
Requires leaffish in hand: Normal leaffish, send shif. Shif effect target leaffish. Opponent's turn, shif ss itself. When you need to interrupt, synchro into arionpos. Arionpos effect, banish zep. Zep effect, special itself and synchro into askaan. Askaan eff, banish itself and opponent's card, chain arionpos eff banish itself search any ghoti, preferably snopios. Askaan eff, banish zep ss itself. 

Requires supay, duskwalker in hand: Activate duskwalker eff, discard and ss itself and supay. Synchro into arionpos. Arionpos eff, banish paces. On your opponent's turn, paces ss itself. When you need interruption, synchro into askaan. Askaan eff banish itself and opponent's card, chain arionpos eff banish itself search a ghoti. Askaan eff, banish paces ss itself. If askaan survives the turn, on your next turn ss paces and make baronne/chengying. 

Requires any water and abyss shark in hand: Normal summon the water. Abyss shark eff ss itself, add silent angler. Silent angler eff ss itself. XYZ into kragen. Kragen is good for controlling the board. If you have gozen kragen is pretty much an auto win. 

Requires snopios in hand + zep in hand/grave + any fish in hand/grave. On opponent's turn, snopios banish the two fish ss itself. Zep eff, ss itself, chain snopios eff target opponent's card/itself. Zep eff, synchro into askaan. If snopios targeted itself, it can add itself back to hand by banishing zep from grave (this won't trigger zep so it will stop some future plays). 

Requires paces/shif in hand + depths: Activate depths, search ixeep. Ixeep eff, ss itself. On opp turn, shif/paces ss itself. You can now make arionpos.

Doodle beasts:
Stego is a free special summon that helps to put dinomorphia traps in the graveyard which then searches doodlebook

Dyna base!?:
The playstyle of Dinomorphia complements this cards summoning condition and can help to bring out Dyna-Tank with a Kentragina for a 4k beatstick without the loss of attack points. deck_excerpt: Utopia Deck, competitive, it can withstand negates and keep going strong
deck_description:
Probably u wonder why i have only 3 onomat monsters? - no, i don't have 3, in total i have 7 onomat monsters and 1 pot of prosperity.

The strongest cards in the deck are Ascended/Armed sage with utopia double because they trigger chain link, that chain link makes cards such as veiller useless.

Important: Zs Utopic Sage is very risky to be played because is easy target for negate and u would end on very weak board if he is negated, that's why i use him in specific combos such as onomatopaira + both ascended armed sages, because the strategy is good enough to withstand negates in the process and make a good board, even if utopic sage was negated.

Why i don't play utopic future draco? It takes too much space, i need to risk playing zs utopic sage too, the strategy to play draco can't withstand negates in the process so is risky and the board i would have if i play draco is: dragonar + leo equiped + number 38 + draco. 

If i don't play Draco, my board is: Dragonar + leo equiped + number 38 + abyss dweller, i consider that stronger board, i have extra space too and the strategy to make that board is much safer and even it can withstand negates in that process, so competitively speaking i don't need draco.

 

NOTES: 

For combos such as onomatopaira + armed sage, the most people are going for zs utopic sage because they want to get to dragonar, i know dragonar is powerful but is safe to go for him with ascended sage , not with utopic sage, to try to get to him with zs utopic sage is VERY HIGH RISK, one negate from the opponent is enough to make u lose the duel, so don't do that, it's too risky ! 

Instead, if u have combo: onomatopaira + armed sage, go for board: Leo ray both equiped tornado and pegasus + Abyss dweller, the strategy can withstand negates in the process and is not risky, the board is also good, keep in mind in the main deck is 10 quick-play spells/traps for going first to make the board even better.

About Dragonic ray, the most of the players doesn't know how to play him, if opponent succeed in negating utopia double then u can summon in his turn dragonic 5000ATK, if the opponent target him u can either support him with pegasus or either make him not targetable by tornado, it's hard combo to deal with, if the opponent doesn't have card like droplet then he need to use his entire hand to counter all of that.

Utopic future slash + downerd magician are used for ZEUS with 6 materials, yea, Zeus with 6 materials is crazy powerful and is worth it, if u combine it with the board breakers/forcing negate cards that i have in main deck, there is no board that i can't break.

 

The side deck is used a lot, deppending if i am first or second, mystic mine can be either target for crossout or u can use it as board breaker going second, u need just 1 utopia and attack with 10000-12000ATK to win the duel.

The cards that can make utopia deck to lose are nibiro and droll, so for going first i have crossout with called by grave, ash blossom is not a big problem but i have it just in case as both target for crossout and as interuption.

the deck can be rebuild in budget version, the expensive cards are just the board breakers /defensive/ forcing negate cards, so there is option for budget too.

there is many combos , but i am lazy to write more
gothon

This deck uses the TCG October 2022 Forbidden and Limited list but uses pre-release cards including Bystial Baldrake.

You can make Accesscode really easy in this deck for OTKs.

Circular is an extender but also a potential starter.

feel free to give me some advice ;)

Centered around getting out Chaos Giant and skill drain. Chaos Giant will be unaffected by skill drains effect while your opponents cards will be. If it comes down to it, use greater polymerization and imperial iron wall. If you bring out chaos giant, it will be unnaffected by anything that woud destroy while imperial iron wall stops it from being banished. Not a totally complicated deck but it does have enough to give other decks a challenge. 

PLEASE COMMENT: I have been working with ancient gears for years, I see the exact same decks on YouTube and im tired of it. Please comment your ideas, I will try them and update as I go.

Fun Note: If you have iron wall on the field, you can keep activating lost wind. Lost wind would usually banish after its second use but iron wall stops that which means you can use its effect over and over as long as your opponent special summons from the extra deck.

UPDATE: I took out mystic mine for the decemeber banlist. I also took out metaverse as it was mostly for mystic mine.

deck_excerpt: Want easy and quick games with a cheap deck for Anti-Spell Festival that can go 1st and 2nd? Zeus Zoodiac is the deck for you!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

This is a Zoodiac deck specifically made for Masterduel's Anti-Spell Festival and it's banlist.

I wanted a no-nonsense straightforward deck to breeze through the Anti-Spell Festival, which wouldn't be mired in the slow slog of constant trap activations on both sides - So I opted to use Zeus Zoodiac!

No complex combos or game knowledge is needed for this deck, hence no gigantic word guide.

Slow down and break your opponent's board with staples like Ash Blossom and Evenly Matched - then turbo out a 2-6 material Zeus with Zoodiac to win!

If your opponent manages to slay your Zeus, your back-up plan is to use Chakanine to revive Drident from the GY, then use Tigermortar to give Drident more material for another destruction of a face-up card.

Jar of Avarice recycles your 1-of cardslike Drident and Zeus in your GY, and Jar of Avarice (as well as any normal trap) is searcheable with Lord of the Heavenly Prison.

My version of Zoodiac is pretty expensive beacause of all the staples, however, this deck's core can be made really cheap. You only need 60 UR for Drident and Zeus, and 90 SR for 3 Thoroughblade. Every other staple card can be anything you want, especially cheap R and N cards.

With Zoodiac, your duels are guaranteed to be fast and straightfoward, giving you a fast way to blaze through Masterduel's Anti-Spell Festival for those sweet, sweet gems.

GLHF Duelists!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: Control oriented Exodia deck with multiple win conditions and no Mystic Mine (but with our boi DPE to help us stall)
deck_description:
(Side deck is still in consideration)

Slow control deck with two main win conditions: Exodia the Forbidden One and Accesscode Talker  and the second wincon feeding right into the first one.  


Main combos are: normal summon Tour Guide From the Underworld to special Sangan from deck then link into Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy for double search;  


Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy + summon or his effect to special from opponent's GY to link into Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians bringing back Witch of the Black Forest then link into Accesscode Talker or Unchained Abomination for a search + a good boss monster.  


Destiny HERO - Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer is an awesome stall and interrupting tool and coupled with the many stall cards in the deck ( Waboku, Battle Fader, Threatening Roar, One Day of Peace. Evenly Matched  ) makes slowing the game down to a pace that you can use to prolong the game for your first win condition to be achievable and/or set up enough searchers to thin the deck and easily get what you need.  


DPE is wonderful alongside The Legendary Exodia Incarnate as it's immune to card effects (be careful since it's also immune to your own Waboku ) so you can effectively pop a card for free by targeting it with DPE's effect.  


Instant Fusion + Millennium-Eyes Restrict is there as one-of combo protection and can be linked once you're done, working as an extender.  

Battle Fader can be searched by Sangan, Witch of the Black Forest and Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy but remember that doing so with the first two of them prevents you from actually using it during that turn.

Relinquished Anima + Wonder Wand can be a tricky little unexpected spot removal after using Battle Fader during your opponent's turn.

 


Potential cuts: Legion the Fiend Jester and White Elephant's Gift  - still not sure about these two, they often feel like a brick more than anything tbh.   Probably would be better if replaced by some kind of staple or handtrap.

Here's my first deck ever

A well rounded rogue deck, many ways for non-destrcution removal based around gren maju and his effect of gaining ATK the number of your banished cards, have some engines that helps achieve victory such as KAIJU, or Danger!.

Most of the matches goes like that

1- Banish as many cards as you can with Pot of desires, Gizmek orochi, Eater of millions.

2- Place 2 level 8 cards (mostly Gizmek orochi + one danger or kaiju) to get Dingirsu on the field to protect gren maju

3- Summon Gren maju and OTK with one attack.


Some tips that can be helpful:

1- Trade-In or Twin twister Gizmek Orochi if you can before summoning him 

2- Trade-In or Twin twister Bigfoot for face-up destruction or Thunderbeard for face-down destruction.


3- Summon Eater of millions with 5 Extra decks, you only want to use him for his non-destrcution banishing.

4- If you only have Ash blossom in your hand you can summon it as tuner + any level 8 monster for Psychic End Punisher.
 
5- Use Necroface for either Allure of darkness or preventing yourself from deck out



I'd appreciate any suggestion on how I can improve the deck.

deck_excerpt: The Destruction Duo is back at it again! Destroy your opponent's cards, destroy your own cards, destroy everything until victory!
deck_description:
This is an Unchained deck tailor made for Masterduel's best-of-1 format.

No complex combos or game knowledge is needed for this deck, hence no 1500 word guide.

Destroy your own cards, disrupt your opponent with Unchained Soul of Rage during their turn, and handtrap them to a standstill. In a game where cards are destroyed by battle or effect, you should be able to outgrind your opponent in a resource war and swing for game!

Handtraps are used instead of the traditional trap cards that Unchained likes to use (Like Torrential Tribute) since handtraps are more suited for a Bo1 game. 13 handtraps should be able to stop your opponent in most circumstances and allow you to get your Unchained deck up and running, whether you go first or second.

I'll end off this article with the wise words of DOOMSLAYER, "RIP AND TEAR UNTIL IT IS DONE." Likewise for Unchained, destroy destroy destroy, until you win!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Rikka Sunavalon Deck that I bring to my locals
deck_description:
This is the Rikka Sunavalon deck that I use the most. I mainly use it to take advantage of my favorite monster in Yu-gi-oh: Tytannial, Princess of Camellias. It has excellent synergy with the deck and is really easy to summon with cards like Lonefire Blossom and Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy, and is searchable with Rikka Glamour. Often times when I open with Unexpected Dai I find myself not using my normal summon, so I use it on Lonefire to get Tytannial out. Of course in the side there is also a Naturia Rosewhip/Bamboo Shoot package and Cactus Bouncer. While less reliable, it is really funny to get these monsters out when my opponent does not see it coming.

There are some things here that are a little less traditional but are more fun for me to play. Tytannial obviously and more ways to get to it, but also Orea the Sylvan High Arbiter. While a fairly slow monster, at the right time it is a great monster for stacking the top of the deck, getting some plants in the graveyard, and clearing the opponent's field for game, and the monster is easily summonable with Strenna like Teardrop and Sacred Tree Beast are. You could swap that out and put a third Strenna in there instead if you prefer. Sylvan Dancepione could probably be swapped out for a third Sunavalon Dryas, but I love the link-2 Dancepione play to go for a Hail Mary and hope you get some useful plants off the top. It is beautiful when it works and often times get you back in the game. I play Rikka Tranquility as well as Rikka Sheet, and it's because I find uses out of both traps and I often use Tranq more than Sheet to keep myself alive. Rikka Flurries is that one card that can take care of almost any tower monster. Even if the monster is unaffected by card effects (Like Crooked Cook or Arrival Cyberse @Ignister), if the monster is the only one the opponent has on the field and you have Flurries and tribute a Rikka, they have to tribute their only monster (The effect is something that affects the player, not the monster, similar to how Evenly Matched works).

The side deck are just cards I prefer to play with the current format, Imperial Iron wall for decks that play out of the banish pile like Floo or Swordsoul, Twin Twisters for back row decks, and Ghost Sister and Spooky Dogwood because it's funny. Change around those cards to your preferences.

I mostly made this to share my creation with the community. Enjoy!
